22 secure drug take-back bin that occurs while the bin is under the control of the collector; (3)
23 post signage notifying customers of the substances that are and are not acceptable for deposit
24 into the secure drug take-back bin; (4) regularly monitor and inspect the bin and surrounding
25 area, including by limiting customer access to the bin to certain hours when the bin is being
26 actively monitored; and (5) maintain records of such inspections and other records required by
27 law. Section 1 also prohibits such a collector from receiving any compensation from a
28 customer to maintain the secure drug take-back bin. Section 1: (1) provides that a collector
29 that complies with such requirements is not subject to discipline by the Board for any injury or
30 harm that directly results from the collector maintaining a secure drug take-back bin, unless
31 the injury or harm directly resulted from the gross negligence or willful and wanton
32 misconduct of the collector; and (2) relieves such a collector from compliance with any
33 restriction established by the governing body of a county, city or other local governmental
34 entity that would affect the collection and destruction of the contents of a secure drug take-
35 back bin.
36 Existing law creates the Fund for a Resilient Nevada and requires the Attorney General to
37 deposit in the Fund money received by this State pursuant to any judgment received or
38 settlement entered into by the State of Nevada as a result of certain litigation concerning the
39 manufacture, distribution, sale or marketing of opioids. Existing law requires the Director
40 of the Department of Health and Human Services to administer the Fund. (NRS 433.732)
41 Section 2 of this bill [appropriates] requires the Director to allocate $500,000 from the
42 Fund to the [Division of Public and Behavioral Health of the Department of Health and
43 Human Services] State Board of Pharmacy to assist collectors with the destruction of home-
44 generated pharmaceutical waste deposited in a secure drug take-back bin.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 639 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. A collector that maintains a secure drug take-back bin for the collection
4 and destruction of home-generated pharmaceutical waste shall:
5 (a) Comply with all applicable state and federal laws and regulations relating
6 to the collection of home-generated pharmaceutical waste for destruction in
7 secure drug take-back bins;
8 (b) Ensure that the secure drug take-back bin is placed in a location that is
9 regularly monitored by employees of the collector;
10 (c) Ensure that conspicuous signage is posted on the secure drug take-back
11 bin that clearly notifies customers as to the substances that are and are not
12 acceptable for deposit into the bin;
13 (d) Ensure that public access to the secure drug take-back bin is limited to
14 hours during which employees of the collector are present and able to monitor
15 the operation of the secure drug take-back bin;
16 (e) Regularly inspect the secure drug take-back bin and the area
17 surrounding the secure drug take-back bin for potential tampering or diversion;
18 (f) Maintain a record of inspections conducted pursuant to paragraph (e)
19 that must:
20 (1) Be documented in writing or electronically and may be combined
21 with records required to be maintained by other state or federal laws or
22 regulations;
23 (2) Include the date and time of each inspection; and
24 (3) Include the initials of the employee who conducted each inspection;
25 (g) Retain each record maintained pursuant to paragraph (f) and any other
26 record relating to the secure drug take-back bin required by state or federal laws

