1 or regulations for at least 2 years after the date of the event to which the record
2 pertains; and
3 (h) Notify at least one local law enforcement agency of any suspected or
4 known tampering or theft or significant loss of controlled substances that occurs
5 while the secure drug take-back bin is under the control of the collector not later
6 than 1 business day after the date on which the tampering, theft or significant
7 loss is suspected or discovered.
8 2. A collector shall not receive compensation from a customer of the
9 collector to maintain a secure drug take-back bin or to perform any act required
10 by subsection 1.
11 3. Any collector that maintains a secure drug take-back bin and complies
12 with the provisions of subsections 1 and 2 is not subject to any:
13 (a) Disciplinary action by the Board for any injury or harm that directly
14 results from the collector maintaining a secure drug take-back bin on its
15 premises, unless the injury or harm directly results from the gross negligence or
16 willful and wanton misconduct of the collector; or
17 (b) Restriction established by the governing body of a county, city or other
18 local governmental entity that would affect the collection, transportation,
19 treatment or destruction of the contents of a secure drug take-back bin pursuant
20 to this section.
21 4. Nothing in this section shall be construed to require any entity that:
22 (a) May qualify as a collector to acquire, maintain or make available to the
23 public a secure drug take-back bin on its premises; or
24 (b) Has entered into an agreement to collect and dispose of solid waste as
25 part of a solid waste management system to collect and dispose of the contents of
26 secure drug take-back bins, unless the agreement or plan expressly provides for
27 such collection and disposal.
28 5. The Board may adopt regulations necessary to carry out the provisions of
29 this section.
30 6. As used in this section:
31 (a) “Collector” means an entity that is:
32 (1) Authorized by and registered with the Drug Enforcement
33 Administration to receive a controlled substance for the purpose of destruction;
34 and
35 (2) In good standing with the Board.
36 (b) “Home-generated pharmaceutical waste” means a pharmaceutical that is
37 no longer wanted or needed by the consumer, including, without limitation, in the
38 form of pills, liquids, inhalers, topical creams, suppositories or patches.
39 (c) “Local law enforcement agency” means:
40 (1) The sheriff’s office of a county;
41 (2) A metropolitan police department; or
42 (3) A police department of an incorporated city.
43 (d) “Maintain” means to own, lease, operate or otherwise host a secure drug
44 take-back bin.
45 (e) “Pharmaceutical” means a drug intended for human or veterinary use,
46 regardless of whether the drug is sold with or without a prescription. The term
47 includes, without limitation, controlled substances listed in schedule II, III, IV or
48 V. The term does not include controlled substances listed in schedule I.
49 (f) “Secure drug take-back bin” means a collection receptacle as described in
50 21 C.F.R. § 1317.75.
51 (g) “Solid waste management system” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS
52 444.500.

